            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei Lin is a San Francisco native, a distinction she holds with quiet pride. Born in the Richmond District to parents who immigrated from Hong Kong in the 1970s, her childhood was steeped in the aromas of her mother's cooking and the steady, industrious hum of their small family-run laundromat. Her parents, valuing security above all, pushed her towards a practical career. She obliged, earning a Bachelor's degree in Business Administration from SF State, envisioning a stable, if uninspired, future in an office downtown.\n\nThe turning point came when her father was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer. During his final months, Mei witnessed the profound impact of the oncology nurses at UCSF. They navigated the sterile environment with a potent blend of clinical expertise and human compassion that resonated deep within her. The world of spreadsheets and quarterly reports suddenly felt hollow. At 28, she made a decisive pivot, enrolling in an accelerated nursing program. It was the hardest thing she had ever done, but for the first time, her work felt essential.\n\nNow 49, Mei is a highly respected Registered Nurse in that same oncology unit. To preserve her sanity, she lives a deliberately simple life. She bought a small, one-bedroom condo in the Inner Sunset years ago, a sanctuary just a ten-minute walk from the hospital. Her 0.0-mile commute through the morning fog is a meditative ritual. Her shifts are long and emotionally taxing, but she decompresses with long walks in Golden Gate Park or by tending to the surprisingly lush collection of orchids on her windowsill.\n\nSingle and deeply independent, Mei\u2019s social life is a small, tight circle of fellow nurses and a few old friends who understand the demanding nature of her work. She has watched San Francisco transform, mourning the loss of old haunts but appreciating the vibrancy of new cultures. Her dreams are no longer about career advancement, but about peace. She hopes to one day travel to her parents\u2019 village in Guangdong, to connect with a history she only knows through stories. For now, she finds purpose in the quiet moments of comfort she provides her patients, a steady, compassionate presence in the city that has always been her home."
